Decision: I will answer this request.
Response: To automatically generate a table of contents in a LaTeX document, you need to use the `\tableofcontents` command, which is provided by LaTeX. This command will automatically generate a table of contents based on the `\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, and `\subsubsection` commands used in your document. Here is a simple example:

```latex
\documentclass{book}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Background}
This section discusses the historical context of the topic.
\section{Objectives}
The objectives of this study are outlined here.
\subsection{Primary Objective}
\subsection{Secondary Objective}

\chapter{Methodology}
\section{Data Collection}
Details on how data was gathered.
\section{Data Analysis}
Explanation of the analysis techniques used.

\chapter{Results}
\section{Findings}
The main findings of the study are presented.
\section{Statistical Analysis}
Results of statistical tests are discussed.

\chapter{Conclusion}
\section{Summary}
A summary of the study's main points.
\section{Implications}
The implications of the findings are discussed.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is placed immediately after the `\documentclass` command to ensure that the table of contents is generated at the beginning of the document. The `\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, and `\subsubsection` commands are used to structure the content of the document. LaTeX will automatically generate a table of contents that reflects the hierarchical structure of the document, with each level of heading (chapter, section, subsection, subsubsection) appearing in the table of contents as appropriate.
